    "explanation": "Work through the math step by step. SLE_before = AV × EF = $500,000 × 0.40 = $200,000. ALE_before = SLE_before × ARO = $200,000 × 0.25 = $50,000. SLE_after = $500,000 × 0.10 = $50,000. ALE_after = $50,000 × 0.25 = $12,500. Savings = ALE_before – ALE_after = $50,000 – $12,500 = $37,500 per year. Net benefit = Savings – Control cost = $37,500 – $30,000 = $7,500. ROSI in dollar terms is $7,500 positive per year; in ratio form, ROSI = $7,500 / $30,000 = 0.25 or 25%, indicating the control pays for itself roughly four times over during its useful life. Option B is correct. Option A is the wrong sign and suggests the candidate subtracted control cost twice or reversed the subtraction. Option C confuses the control cost ($30,000) with the net benefit. Option D inflates the benefit, likely by ignoring the ARO and treating the full SLE reduction as an annual figure. CISSP quantitative risk questions require mechanical arithmetic and attention to units — always confirm whether the final figure is a dollar value, a ratio, or a percentage.",
