    "explanation": "The scenario describes an attacker who gains administrative privileges by forging a token whose signature the application fails to verify. The core violation is that the attacker ends up with more privilege than they should have — specifically, admin privilege they were never granted. That is elevation of privilege (EoP), which violates the authorization security property. Option C is correct. Option A (Spoofing) is plausible because the attacker is impersonating an admin, but STRIDE's Spoofing specifically concerns the establishment of identity at the boundary — a better fit for 'the attacker logs in as someone else'. Here, the attacker does not log in; the attacker manipulates an authorization claim to gain privilege. Option B (Tampering) is also defensible because the attacker modifies the token, but STRIDE treats tampering primarily as an integrity violation of data at rest or in transit between known principals, not as a privilege-gaining attack on an auth token. Option D (Information disclosure) does not fit because the attack escalates privilege rather than exfiltrating data. The exam rewards the BEST answer. CISSP categorizes this canonical attack pattern as EoP because the outcome — privilege escalation — defines it. The underlying technical fix is signature validation on all inbound tokens, which is both a Tampering mitigation (protecting the token from modification) and an Elevation-of-privilege mitigation (preventing the forged token from granting unauthorized access).",
