    "correct_index": 2,
    "explanation": "Data in use — data actively being processed by an application — is the hardest state to protect because the CPU requires plaintext to operate on. Traditional at-rest encryption (AES, for example) stops providing protection once the data is loaded into memory for processing; traditional in-transit encryption (TLS) stops providing protection once the data is decrypted at an endpoint. Modern approaches to in-use protection include confidential computing (Intel SGX/TDX, AMD SEV, AWS Nitro Enclaves, Azure Confidential VMs), homomorphic encryption (computation on ciphertext, practical only for specific operations), and secure multi-party computation. Option A (at rest) is well-protected by symmetric encryption. Option B (in transit) is well-protected by TLS, IPsec, and SSH. Option D (archived data) is a special case of at rest and benefits from the same controls. The CISSP exam tests data states because candidates commonly assume that at-rest encryption covers all three states, which is the single most common Domain 2 conceptual error. When a scenario describes data actively being analyzed, queried, or computed on, the answer is not 'encrypt it' — it is 'protect it in memory with state-specific controls'.",
