    "explanation": "Hospitals disposing of SSDs containing PHI must comply with HIPAA's media disposal requirements (45 CFR §164.310(d)), which require secure destruction or rendering of the media so that PHI cannot be retrieved. NIST SP 800-88 Rev 1 is the authoritative sanitization guide and recognizes cryptographic erase as Purge when the SED is properly implemented and the key is verifiably destroyed. For drives that do not support verified crypto-erase, or where verification is uncertain, physical destruction (shredding, pulverization, incineration) is appropriate to achieve Destroy-level assurance. Option B captures this combined approach. Option A (single-pass overwrite) is a Clear-level technique that NIST no longer recommends as the primary method for SSDs because wear-leveling and over-provisioning mean overwrites may not reach all blocks. Option C (degaussing) does not work on SSDs because they have no magnetic media — this is a favorite distractor on the exam. Option D (format + defragmentation) does not remove data blocks and is not a sanitization method at all. The manager-mindset point is that sanitization choice is driven by media type, classification, and verification capability — not by a single default. A mature program maintains a sanitization decision matrix and produces a certificate of destruction for each medium.",
