    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Removing direct identifiers (name, email, SSN) does not anonymize a dataset if quasi-identifiers remain. A famous Sweeney (2000) study demonstrated that 87% of the US population can be uniquely identified by the combination of ZIP code, birth date, and gender alone — exactly the combination described in this scenario. Under GDPR, a dataset is anonymized only when re-identification is not reasonably possible considering all the means likely to be used, including by a third party; pseudonymized data — where re-identification remains possible through a key or through quasi-identifier linkage — is still personal data. Option B is correct. Option A is the common trap and reflects a naive view of anonymization that does not survive modern re-identification research. Option C confuses removal of direct identifiers with public-domain data, which is a different concept entirely; the data is still personal data of the affected individuals. Option D is wrong because GDPR's research exception (Article 89) provides some flexibility but does not exempt personal data from GDPR entirely — controllers must still implement technical and organizational measures and must respect data subject rights where compatible with the research purpose. The CISSP exam tests this pattern because candidates routinely underestimate the power of quasi-identifier linkage. A mature privacy program requires a formal anonymization assessment (e.g., ISO/IEC 20889 de-identification techniques) before treating a dataset as outside GDPR scope.",
