    "correct_index": 2,
    "explanation": "The requirement is that the cloud provider must not be able to read the data under any circumstances. Client-side encryption with customer-held, customer-managed keys outside the provider's environment is the only control design that satisfies this requirement: the provider sees only ciphertext and never has access to the decryption key. Option C captures this correctly. Option A (server-side with provider-managed keys) leaves the provider in full control of both ciphertext and keys — the provider can decrypt at will. Option B (customer-managed keys in the provider's KMS) is an improvement because the customer controls key policy, but the key material lives inside the provider's infrastructure and is accessible to the provider under legal process (compelled disclosure), insider access, or key-service compromise; for customers who require that the provider be technically unable to decrypt, KMS-resident keys are insufficient. Option D (physical security) does nothing to prevent the provider's own personnel from accessing data. The CISSP exam tests the trust boundary of cloud encryption because practitioners routinely conflate 'encrypted' with 'provider cannot read'. The distinction matters in regulated sectors, for law enforcement resistance, and for geopolitical risk management. Be aware of related concepts: Bring Your Own Key (BYOK), Hold Your Own Key (HYOK), and the increasing availability of provider-side confidential computing (e.g., AWS Nitro Enclaves, Azure Confidential Computing) that narrow the trust boundary but do not eliminate it.",
