    "explanation": "Payroll records contain personal data including salary, bank details, tax information, and identifiers such as national insurance or social security numbers. For an EU resident, this data is subject to GDPR including Article 9 special categories where health-related or similar elements are present, and to strict handling requirements even where it is not special category. Most mature classification schemes place payroll records at the Restricted level because the combination of sensitivity, regulatory exposure (GDPR, tax law, employment law), and individual harm from disclosure (identity theft, discrimination, personal safety) justifies the highest commercial classification. Option D is correct. Option A (Public) would be grossly inappropriate and would violate GDPR, employment law, and common sense. Option B (Internal) under-classifies and would permit handling (e.g., unrestricted internal distribution) that is incompatible with GDPR Article 5 principles of purpose limitation and data minimization. Option C (Confidential) is closer but still under-classifies: Restricted (or equivalent top-tier) handling — encrypted at rest, access strictly limited to payroll and HR with logging, no email distribution, retention per employment-law schedules — is the appropriate bar. The CISSP exam tests classification judgment because practitioners often classify data by the comfort level of the organization ('we've always called this Confidential') rather than by the harm potential and regulatory exposure. Payroll data is one of the textbook Restricted-classification examples alongside health records, payment card data, and credentials.",
