    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "HITECH (the Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act, enacted in 2009) and the subsequent 2013 HIPAA Omnibus Rule made clear that subcontractors of business associates who handle PHI are themselves business associates, and that a written business associate agreement (BAA) is required between the business associate and each subcontractor handling PHI. This is the 'flow-down' rule for HIPAA compliance, and it applies regardless of how many tiers of subcontracting are involved. Option B captures this correctly. Option A is wrong and represents pre-HITECH thinking that left subcontractors in a regulatory gap; the Omnibus Rule closed that gap. Option C confuses business associate status with covered entity status — subcontractors handling PHI on behalf of a business associate are business associates, not covered entities. Option D is wrong because the original BAA between the covered entity and the service provider does not bind the sub-processor; each tier must have its own BAA. The CISSP exam tests this explicitly because many real-world HIPAA incidents involve cloud sub-processors that were improperly brought into the covered-entity ecosystem without flow-down BAAs. A compliant architecture requires BAA flow-down at every tier where PHI access or storage exists, and the covered entity retains accountability even when the compromised party is two or three tiers away in the supply chain.",
