    "explanation": "Health data triggers multiple compliance regimes and substantial individual harm potential. GDPR Article 9 treats health data as special category data requiring an explicit lawful basis beyond ordinary Article 6 bases — typically explicit consent or specific exceptions for medical care or public health. HIPAA applies if the company is a covered entity or a business associate, imposing additional handling requirements and breach notification obligations on PHI. State-level laws add further specific risks: reproductive health information has become a target of state law enforcement in some US jurisdictions following Dobbs (2022), and menstrual cycle data has specific exposure in those contexts; Washington's My Health My Data Act (2024) imposes additional obligations on consumer health data outside HIPAA; California and Connecticut have their own sensitive-data rules. The classification must be at the highest tier (Restricted/equivalent), handling must include strict minimization (collect only what the insights actually require), explicit consent for special category use, strong technical controls (encryption, authenticated access only, no third-party sharing without explicit consent, no cross-jurisdictional transfers without assessment), and privacy-by-design architecture. Option B captures these layered considerations. Option A grossly under-classifies consumer-facing health data. Option C confuses 'voluntary entry' with 'public' — voluntary entry into a private system is not public disclosure, and the data remains highly sensitive. Option D abdicates the CISSP's advisory role, which explicitly covers risk and regulatory analysis for the CTO and product team to act on. The CISSP exam increasingly tests consumer health data because it is one of the most rapidly evolving regulatory landscapes and because CISSPs are routinely the only role in the product team who understands the full regulatory surface.",
