    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Discovering a long-standing access anomaly requires balancing the risk of leaving it in place against the risk of abrupt change — the latter can cause outages, disrupt legitimate troubleshooting, and damage the CISSP's relationship with the engineering team. The correct response is to document the current state (what access exists, who holds it, what it is used for), assess the actual risk (classification of the data, observed usage patterns, detection coverage, insider threat profile), identify the legitimate needs the access serves (which rarely disappear — developers really do need some kind of production troubleshooting access), and propose a compensating-control redesign that approximates the intent of the original policy while preserving legitimate work. The redesign typically includes break-glass access with enhanced logging, least-privilege roles for specific troubleshooting tasks, time-limited credentials, and an approval workflow for sensitive operations. The remediation must route through change management and require the data owner's approval because the affected data has a classification and an owner. Option B captures this approach. Option A (revoke immediately) creates operational risk without addressing the underlying need and often results in the access being restored worse than before. Option C accepts a governance failure and is not defensible. Option D (password rotation) is security theater — it does nothing about the excess privilege. The CISSP exam rewards the document-assess-redesign-approve sequence because it reflects how mature security programs address inherited risk without causing self-inflicted outages. The pattern generalizes to any long-standing, undocumented access finding: preserve business continuity while improving the posture, with documented ownership, rather than a unilateral crackdown.",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 2
