    "explanation": "The customer's requirement — isolation at every layer — is a physical/infrastructure tenancy requirement, not a logical one. Logical isolation through schemas or row-level filters in a shared multi-tenant database cannot satisfy the request because a compromise of the shared compute or storage layer would cross tenant boundaries. The architectural pattern that satisfies the requirement is infrastructure-level tenancy: dedicated compute instances, dedicated storage (separate databases, separate object-store buckets, separate encryption keys), dedicated network segments, and ideally tenant-controlled keys held outside the shared KMS. This is sometimes called 'single-tenant' or 'pod-per-tenant' architecture and trades multi-tenant economies of scale for isolation and regulatory defensibility. Option B captures this correctly. Option A (schema isolation) is logical isolation and does not meet the requirement. Option C (field-level encryption alone) is a useful control but does not isolate the compute, storage, or network layers and does not satisfy the architectural requirement. Option D (separate accounts in the same database) is logical, not physical. The CISSP exam tests multi-tenancy because it is one of the defining design trade-offs in modern SaaS architecture and because regulatory and customer requirements increasingly push toward stronger isolation than pure multi-tenancy provides. Related concepts: confidential computing at the tenant level, Bring Your Own Cloud (BYOC) deployments where the SaaS runs in the customer's cloud account, and the CSA Cloud Controls Matrix's guidance on multi-tenant isolation. The correct manager-mindset framing is that isolation requirements are customer-driven and must be costed, documented, and governed at contract level.",
