    "correct_index": 0,
    "explanation": "The scenario combines several failures. First, MD5 is fast, which means the hash offers almost no resistance to brute-force enumeration. Second, the inputs (usernames) are low-entropy and often predictable, so an attacker can precompute MD5 hashes for likely usernames. Third, the hashes are unsalted, which means the same username always produces the same hash — a rainbow table attack is trivial. Fourth, MD5 is cryptographically broken for collision resistance (not directly relevant to authentication but a sign of an overall weak primitive). Fifth, and most fundamentally, the design assumes that the hash of a username is a secret, but it is not — it is a deterministic function of a predictable input. The session tokens can therefore be recovered by anyone with knowledge of usernames and MD5. The fix is not to strengthen the hash but to redesign the scheme: session tokens should be cryptographically-random values (at least 128 bits of entropy, ideally 256), generated per session, stored server-side and associated with session state, and transmitted to the client as opaque identifiers. The client never needs to derive or recompute them. Option A captures the compound nature of the failure. Options B, C, and D each identify a single issue but miss the central point. The CISSP exam tests this pattern because session-token generation is one of the most commonly-broken controls, and the correct answer is architectural (random tokens) rather than primitive-level (stronger hash).",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 3
