    "explanation": "Custom-designed cryptographic protocols have a catastrophic track record. Even protocols designed by people with strong mathematical and security backgrounds have failed, including protocols from major organizations that passed their own internal review. Kerckhoffs' principle states that security should depend only on the secrecy of the key, and a corollary is that the protocol itself must withstand public scrutiny — internal testing is not public cryptanalysis and cannot substitute for it. The phrase 'don't roll your own crypto' captures the accumulated wisdom: use standardized, peer-reviewed, widely-implemented protocols (TLS 1.3 for transport, Signal Protocol for messaging, NaCl/libsodium for application crypto, JSON Web Tokens with standard signing algorithms for authentication) rather than custom designs. Option B captures this. Option A accepts a risk the CISSP exam explicitly teaches against. Option C (more documentation) does not fix the underlying problem — the protocol's security cannot be established by reading vendor documentation. Option D (pilot deployment) exposes real customers to an unvalidated protocol and does not produce the cryptanalysis needed to validate it. The CISSP exam tests this pattern repeatedly because it is one of the clearest examples of the 'technology answer' being wrong and the 'boring standardized answer' being right. The right answer to 'should we build our own encryption' is almost always 'no, use a standard'.",
