    "explanation": "A shared pre-shared key across all contractors combines three failures: (1) no per-user isolation — compromise of one contractor's credential (phishing, insider misuse, laptop theft, negligent sharing) compromises access for all contractors, effectively turning the shared key into a shared secret with a large and untrustworthy audience; (2) no granular revocation — dismissing a single contractor requires rotating the shared key and redistributing it to everyone who remains, which is operationally painful and often delayed; (3) no accountability — VPN logs cannot attribute activity to individual contractors, defeating audit and investigation. The correct design issues a per-contractor credential (certificate from a trusted CA, per-user key pair, or user-specific EAP method), enrolls contractors individually, logs per-user activity, and revokes on termination. Option B captures these concerns. Option A (speed) is not the issue. Option C (deprecation) is not accurate — PSKs are still supported in IPsec but should be avoided for multi-user scenarios. Option D (split tunneling) is a separate design choice. The CISSP exam tests per-user credentialing because it is a foundational access control principle.",
