    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "DNS-based load balancing and routing depends on DNS responses that can be observed, cached, and potentially manipulated. The security-relevant considerations for the design are: (1) DNSSEC signing of authoritative records so that resolvers can verify integrity; (2) health checks that automatically remove compromised or unreachable regions from the DNS rotation so users are not routed to bad endpoints; (3) multi-provider DNS to avoid a single-provider failure (Dyn 2016 outage affected many major services because they depended on a single DNS provider); (4) short TTLs on DNS records to enable fast failover when a region is removed from rotation, balanced against the load on authoritative servers; (5) privacy considerations for the routing metadata exposed to DNS. Option B captures the compound architectural consideration. Option A dismisses DNS security. Options C and D are not operationally viable. The CISSP exam tests DNS architecture because it is a critical, widely-used, and widely-misconfigured component of network design.",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 4
