    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Cloud Access Security Brokers provide visibility and control over SaaS applications — the major blind spot in traditional perimeter security. The three deployment modes each address different aspects of the problem. API mode uses vendor APIs (Microsoft 365, Google Workspace, Salesforce, Slack, etc.) to inspect data already in the SaaS application: content DLP, shared-file scanning, anomaly detection. It is post-hoc (not in-line) but has full visibility into sanctioned apps. Forward proxy mode sits between users and SaaS, inspecting traffic in flight — it provides real-time control including DLP on outbound data and access control to unsanctioned apps. Reverse proxy mode requires SaaS-vendor support (SAML-integrated proxy) and works only for specific applications. Mature deployments combine API mode for sanctioned apps (deep content visibility) with forward proxy for broader visibility into unsanctioned SaaS and in-line control, integrated with ZTNA and SWG in a SASE architecture. Option B captures this nuanced framing. Option A dismisses a legitimate tool class. Option C is oversimplified. Option D is wrong. The CISSP exam tests CASB because SaaS governance is a growing area and because CASB mode selection has real operational and visibility consequences.",
