    "explanation": "Service accounts are often the weakest link in enterprise IAM because they are created ad-hoc, passwords are stored in code or config, rotation is painful, and ownership is unclear. The correct remediation is a structured program: (1) inventory — discover every service account across Active Directory, cloud IAM (AWS, Azure, GCP), databases, SaaS applications, and custom applications; (2) classify — prioritize by criticality (domain admin, cloud root, production database, etc.); (3) bring under management — credential vaulting (store passwords in a vault and have applications retrieve them at runtime), certificate-based authentication (mutual TLS with short-lived certs), managed service accounts where available (Windows gMSA, cloud workload identity federation), and rotation automation; (4) monitor for anomalies — unusual authentication patterns, credential usage from unexpected sources, bulk operations that suggest compromise; (5) integrate with JML governance — each service account has an owner responsible for its lifecycle, and ownership transfers when the owner leaves. Option B captures this full program. Option A (delete all) breaks every application. Option C (shared account) is catastrophic. Option D (give to developers) bypasses governance. The CISSP exam tests service account management because it is a major modern IAM gap and because the remediation is structured and testable.",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 5
