    "explanation": "CIAM (Customer Identity and Access Management) differs from workforce IAM along several dimensions. Account ownership: in workforce IAM, the organization owns the account (can reset, deprovision, audit at will); in CIAM, the user owns the account and the organization is subject to privacy law and consumer expectations. User experience: workforce IAM can impose friction (users have no choice); CIAM is competitive, and bad UX loses customers. Consent and privacy: CIAM is governed by GDPR, CCPA, and similar consumer privacy laws, and data collection must be transparent and lawful; workforce IAM has HR and employment law considerations but different constraints. Authentication: workforce can mandate FIDO2 or smart cards; CIAM must work with whatever authenticators users have, often starting with email or phone verification and adding stronger factors as optional or incentivized. Scalability: CIAM is consumer-grade with millions of users and extreme traffic variability (flash sales, viral events); workforce IAM is typically tens of thousands to low millions. Fraud detection: CIAM has fraudulent account creation, credential stuffing, account takeover as first-class concerns; workforce IAM has insider threat as the comparable concern. Option B captures these dimensions. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests CIAM because it is increasingly a specialized area and because the differences from workforce IAM are not always obvious.",
