    "explanation": "MFA is one of the most valuable security controls and has measurably reduced credential-based attacks, but the claim that it 'solves' credential theft is an oversimplification that has produced false confidence. Attackers have evolved past traditional MFA: real-time phishing relay defeats SMS, TOTP, and some push notifications by relaying credentials to the real site in the window before they expire; MFA fatigue attacks exploit push notifications by spamming users until they approve a prompt (Uber 2022); session cookie theft bypasses MFA entirely by stealing the cookie after authentication; OAuth consent phishing tricks users into granting application access that does not require re-authentication; SIM swap attacks defeat SMS-based MFA by transferring the phone number. Phishing-resistant MFA (FIDO2, smart cards) defeats most of these attacks but does not address all of them — session theft and OAuth consent phishing still work post-authentication. The mature response is defense in depth: phishing-resistant MFA plus session protection (short lifetimes, device binding, continuous risk evaluation), plus conditional access (device posture, location, time), plus continuous monitoring for anomalies, plus incident response readiness. Option B captures this nuanced view. Options A, C, D are wrong in different ways.",
