    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Break-glass accounts solve a specific problem: when the normal IdP is unavailable (outage, misconfiguration, attack, DR scenario), administrators still need a way to access critical systems. The design must balance security against availability: the accounts must work when needed but must not be abused or compromised. The mature pattern is: (1) a small number of pre-enrolled break-glass accounts, not one per admin; (2) strong credentials (long random passwords, hardware keys, or both) stored in physical safes with dual-access controls (two people must cooperate to retrieve); (3) dual-custody procedures so that any use requires two authorized individuals; (4) monitoring alerts that fire immediately when a break-glass account is used, triggering incident response even before the use is complete; (5) periodic exercise of the accounts in DR drills so they are known to work; (6) post-use reviews for every activation to confirm legitimate use and to reset the credentials afterward. Option B captures this. Option A (no break-glass) creates a reliability failure at the worst possible moment. Options C and D are reckless. The CISSP exam tests break-glass because it is a specific, testable pattern where the 'right answer' balances security and availability explicitly.",
