    "explanation": "95% of accounts in Domain Admins is an extreme violation of least privilege and represents a catastrophic vulnerability: any compromise of any account enables full domain compromise. The remediation is a structured, multi-phase program: (1) role analysis — identify who actually performs domain admin functions (typically a small team); (2) tiered admin model per Microsoft's Privileged Access Workstation guidance — tier-0 for systems that manage the identity infrastructure itself (domain controllers, PKI, identity management systems), tier-1 for member servers, tier-2 for user workstations; each tier is isolated from the others so that a compromise at a lower tier cannot escalate; (3) migrate users out of Domain Admins to right-sized groups — most current members will not need it; (4) for users who occasionally need elevated access, implement just-in-time elevation through a PAM system rather than permanent membership; (5) implement Privileged Access Workstations for tier-0 admins — hardened, dedicated workstations used only for administrative tasks, isolated from email and web; (6) enforce ongoing access recertification so that membership in high-privilege groups is regularly revalidated; (7) monitor for anomalous use of admin privileges. Option B captures this structured approach. Options A, C, D are reckless. The CISSP exam tests this scenario because it is common in poorly-managed AD environments and because the remediation is specific.",
