    "explanation": "SOC 2 Type I attests to the design of controls at a specific point in time — it tells you whether the vendor had the controls in place on a particular date. Type II attests to the operating effectiveness of the controls over a period, typically 6 to 12 months of auditor observation and testing. For enterprise vendor evaluation, Type II is significantly stronger evidence because it demonstrates that the controls actually worked in practice, not merely that they existed on a snapshot date. Accepting Type I as sufficient is a common mistake in vendor assessment; it gives the vendor credit for design without verifying execution. The correct response is to request Type II. If the vendor does not have Type II (common for new vendors who have just completed their first audit cycle), the CISSP should negotiate a timeline: accept Type I for the interim with a commitment to deliver Type II within 12 months, and re-evaluate at that point. Option B captures this. Option A accepts weaker evidence. Option C (SOC 1) is the wrong report type for security controls evaluation. Option D (reject entirely) is too absolute when a timeline-based path exists. The CISSP exam tests this because SOC 2 Type I vs Type II is one of the most commonly-missed distinctions in vendor evaluation.",
