    "explanation": "'Continuous compliance monitoring' is a popular vendor framing that covers a wide range of actual capabilities. The mature evaluation asks specific questions about what the system actually does: (1) What specific controls are monitored? Some 'continuous' tools check only a subset of relevant controls and leave others for periodic manual assessment. (2) What is the detection latency for a control failure? A tool that reports drift the next day is different from one that reports in real time. (3) How is remediation tracked? Detection without remediation is security theater; the tool should integrate with ticketing or workflow. (4) How does the system handle false positives without losing signal quality? Over-alerting drives users to dismiss all alerts, which destroys the value of monitoring. Other important questions include: what evidence is captured for audit; how does the tool integrate with SOC 2 / ISO 27001 / PCI-DSS frameworks; what is the operational cost beyond licensing; and how is the system itself kept current with changing compliance requirements. Option B captures the specific evaluation questions. Options A, C, D are either frivolous or secondary. The CISSP exam tests vendor evaluation because CISSPs are routinely asked to assess security tooling and should be able to distinguish marketing from substance.",
