    "explanation": "Annual pentests alone are insufficient because they provide a point-in-time view of security posture and miss everything that happens between tests. A production environment can drift significantly in 364 days: new services deployed, configurations changed, new vulnerabilities disclosed, new attack techniques developed. A mature assessment strategy is layered: (1) continuous vulnerability scanning that catches known vulnerabilities as they emerge; (2) continuous configuration monitoring that catches drift from baselines; (3) automated compliance checks that catch policy violations in real time; (4) internal red team exercises that test detection and response between formal pentests; (5) periodic external pentests (annually or more frequently) that provide independent validation and find the things internal tools miss; (6) bug bounty programs that provide a continuous external attacker perspective. The combination gives ongoing visibility rather than a snapshot. Option B captures this layered framing. Option A (cost) is a consideration but not the primary concern. Option C (inaccurate) overstates pentest weakness. Option D (monthly) is operationally impractical and misses the broader point that different techniques have different cadences. The CISSP exam tests assessment strategy because program maturity depends on diversification of assessment methods.",
