    "explanation": "'Collect everything' is one of the most common SIEM anti-patterns. Log volume scales with environment, and ingesting every log source at the highest verbosity produces massive storage costs, analyst overload, and a haystack in which real signals drown. The mature approach is use-case-driven: (1) define specific detection use cases that the SIEM should support — for example, 'detect lateral movement via SMB', 'detect credential stuffing at authentication endpoints', 'detect data exfiltration via DNS'; (2) identify the specific log sources and fields needed for each use case; (3) tune ingestion to support detection objectives, including parsing, enrichment, and field extraction; (4) build, test, and tune correlation rules against real traffic; (5) measure detection effectiveness and false-positive rates; (6) evolve scope as new use cases are added. This 'detection-as-code' approach produces actionable alerts rather than noise. Option B captures this. Option A (collect everything) is the anti-pattern. Option C (only firewall) is over-restrictive. Option D (turn off alerting) destroys the purpose of the SIEM. The CISSP exam tests SIEM design because it is an area where tool acquisition frequently outpaces operational capacity and where the mature answer is specific.",
