    "explanation": "Annual recertification is often a paper exercise where managers click through hundreds of entitlements without meaningful review. Improvements that make recertification effective: (1) tier the cadence by sensitivity — quarterly or continuous for privileged access, annually for standard access, driven by risk rather than uniform frequency; (2) positive attestation model — unattested access is automatically revoked rather than defaulted to accepted, which creates pressure to actually review; (3) analytics-driven focus — use peer comparison and anomaly detection to identify users with outlier entitlements (more access than their peers, unused access, access out of pattern), and focus review on those cases rather than blanket review of everything; (4) integration with joiner-mover-leaver so that movers trigger targeted re-review rather than waiting for the next cycle; (5) reviewer training so that managers understand what they are attesting to; (6) measurement of outcomes (access removed as a result of review) as the program KPI, not 'users certified'. Option A captures this improvement. Options B, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests recertification because it is one of the most common governance controls and one of the most frequently-ineffective in practice.",
