    "explanation": "DR and IR procedures are useless until they have been tested in conditions that simulate real events. The mature testing approach runs exercises at increasing levels of realism: (1) checklist review — paper verification that procedures and contact lists are current; (2) tabletop exercise — discussion-based walkthrough where participants describe what they would do in a scenario; (3) walkthrough — detailed step-by-step review of each procedure with subject matter experts; (4) simulation — partial execution in a test environment; (5) parallel test — recovery procedures executed in a second environment while primary operations continue; (6) full interruption test — shutting down primary to force real failover. Each level catches different gaps. Every exercise should produce a debrief that identifies gaps, updates procedures, and updates training. The improvement over time (measured by exercise outcomes, gap closure rate, and ultimately real-incident performance) is tracked as a program KPI. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are insufficient. The CISSP exam tests DR/IR exercise design because it is specific, testable, and frequently a failure point in real incidents — procedures exist on paper but are never exercised, and nobody notices until an actual incident reveals the gap.",
