    "explanation": "Executive-level metrics should be outcome-focused and trending over time. Option B captures a mature set of KRIs: (1) percentage of critical risks within appetite — the central question of risk governance; (2) percentage of critical vulnerabilities past SLA — program effectiveness at managing the most important vulnerabilities; (3) mean time to detect / respond for significant incidents — operational effectiveness of the detection and response capability; (4) percentage of critical vendors with current assessments — supply chain risk management effectiveness; (5) predicted trend in the next quarter — forward-looking indicator for executive planning. All of these are outcome metrics that map to specific actions the executives can take: approve investment, escalate to the board, adjust risk appetite. They also all trend over time, so executives can see whether the program is improving or degrading. Options A, C, D are activity metrics that measure work, not effectiveness. The CISSP exam tests executive metric selection because it is a specific area where the manager mindset produces the right answer: metrics should enable decisions, not display effort. Related concepts: KPIs (performance metrics), KRIs (risk metrics), and the difference between leading indicators (predictive) and lagging indicators (historical).",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 6
