    "explanation": "Infrastructure-as-code brings benefits (reproducibility, versioning, peer review, automation) but it is not self-validating. IaC templates can encode insecure configurations: publicly-exposed buckets, over-permissive IAM roles, missing encryption, weak authentication — all as code. The templates themselves must be assessed: (1) linting and policy-as-code scanning (Checkov, Terraform Sentinel, OPA/Rego for cloud policies, AWS Config Rules, Azure Policy, GCP Organization Policies) to detect known-bad patterns before deployment; (2) peer review of template changes through code review processes; (3) runtime state validation to detect drift from templates (sometimes an emergency fix is applied directly, bypassing the pipeline, and the template no longer reflects reality); (4) continuous cloud security posture management (CSPM) tools that assess deployed resources against benchmarks regardless of how they got there. Option B captures the layered approach. Option A (IaC is self-validating) is the common misconception that the existence of IaC makes security automatic. Option C (IaC is insecure) overstates the concern. Option D (if developers are senior) relies on individual expertise rather than systematic process. The CISSP exam tests cloud assessment because cloud is now the dominant deployment model and because the assessment practices differ from traditional on-premises.",
