    "explanation": "Starting a pentest program requires risk-based prioritization — not attempting to test everything at once. The correct first step is to identify the most critical and most-exposed systems (internet-facing applications, systems handling the most sensitive data, recently-changed major systems, systems with known potential vulnerabilities) and scope an initial pentest for those. The engagement should include: (1) clear rules of engagement and authorization letter; (2) scope defined by the prioritization; (3) remediation obligation for findings; (4) retest to confirm remediation is effective; (5) deliverables (executive summary, technical report, remediation plan). Beyond the initial engagement, the organization should build an ongoing program: cadence (typically annually for most systems, more frequently for internet-facing), scope that expands over time, integration with the vulnerability management workflow, and measurement of outcomes (findings per test, remediation time, repeat findings). Option B captures this staged approach. Option A (test everything immediately) is operationally infeasible and would produce low-quality results from rushed engagement. Option C (one contractor for everything) does not reflect scope or prioritization. Option D (firewalls instead) is a category error. The CISSP exam tests program building because it is specific to the manager mindset of starting where the risk is highest.",
