    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "A SOC 2 Type II report has several sections, and the substance lives in the detailed testing results. Key things to look for: (1) the auditor's opinion — unqualified means controls were operating effectively, qualified means there were specific exceptions, adverse means controls were not effective, disclaimer means the auditor could not form an opinion; (2) any control exceptions, deviations, or qualifications noted during testing, which indicate specific weaknesses the auditor identified; (3) the complementary user entity controls (CUECs) — controls that the customer (you) are responsible for implementing to complete the control environment, because the vendor's controls depend on customer actions (for example, 'customer is responsible for managing user access within their tenant'); (4) any subservice organizations and how they are included or excluded; (5) the scope description and how accurately it reflects the services actually being consumed. The detailed testing results and the auditor's opinion tell you whether to trust the vendor's controls; the CUECs tell you what you must do on your side to complete the control picture. Option B captures these. Option A (executive summary) is high-level and does not contain exceptions. Options C and D are frivolous. The CISSP exam tests SOC 2 analysis because evaluating SOC 2 reports is a specific, operational skill CISSPs need in vendor management.",
