    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Bug bounty programs are valuable but complex to run successfully. The key considerations: (1) scope — what systems are in and out of scope, what kinds of testing are authorized, what specific behaviors are prohibited (denial of service, social engineering, accessing real user data); (2) disclosure — use security.txt (RFC 9116) and a public program page so researchers know how to contact the organization; (3) severity categories with clear payout ranges so researchers can estimate reward before reporting; (4) prompt response to submissions — acknowledgement within hours to days, triage within days, remediation based on severity, payment promptly after triage (slow payment destroys program reputation among researchers); (5) safe-harbor policy — a published commitment that the organization will not pursue legal action against researchers acting within scope and good faith, typically language referencing DOJ guidance or the EFF Safe Harbor template; (6) program as complement, not replacement — pentests find things bug bounty does not, and vice versa. Option B captures these. Option A (largest bounties) is secondary; researchers value response time and fairness at least as much as money. Option C is discriminatory and operationally harmful. Option D misses that bug bounty and pentest are complementary. The CISSP exam tests bug bounty because it is an increasingly common program model.",
    "tags": [],
    "domain": 6
