    "explanation": "Publishing security information publicly involves a trade-off between transparency (which builds customer trust and attracts researcher engagement) and operational security (which limits what attackers can learn). The mature approach is selective: (1) publish high-level architecture — what security principles the organization follows, what frameworks are adopted, what certifications are held, what general patterns are in use; (2) publish security principles and commitments — data handling, encryption, authentication, incident response, disclosure policies; (3) publish bug bounty scope so researchers know what is in bounds; (4) maintain private detail about specific configurations, rule sets, control effectiveness, and operational runbooks — these aid attackers without proportional benefit to researchers; (5) publish post-mortems and incident summaries after resolution — these build trust and contribute to community learning, but require careful editing to avoid revealing operational details that still matter; (6) use coordinated disclosure for vulnerabilities found by researchers, acknowledging contributions publicly while protecting specific technical details during remediation. Option B captures this balance. Option A (full disclosure always) sacrifices operational security. Option C (everything secret) sacrifices trust and researcher engagement. Option D is wrong. The CISSP exam tests disclosure policy because it is a real governance decision with both business and security dimensions.",
