    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "NIST SP 800-61 Rev 2 'Computer Security Incident Handling Guide' defines four phases of the incident response lifecycle: (1) Preparation — policies, procedures, team, tools, training, and exercises before any incident occurs; (2) Detection and Analysis — recognizing that an incident has occurred and triaging severity and scope; (3) Containment, Eradication, and Recovery — stopping the spread, removing the threat's presence, and restoring operations; (4) Post-Incident Activity — debrief, lessons learned, program improvement. Option B states this exactly. Option A (PDCA) is a general management cycle, not the IR lifecycle specifically. Option C is close to the NIST Cybersecurity Framework's first four functions (Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond) but misses 'Recover' and is not the IR lifecycle. Option D is similar to the CSF functions and not the specific IR lifecycle. The CISSP exam tests NIST SP 800-61 directly because it is the canonical IR reference and because candidates need to distinguish the IR lifecycle from related but different frameworks. Memorize: Preparation → Detection & Analysis → Containment, Eradication, Recovery → Lessons Learned.",
