    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "The 3-2-1 rule is a widely-cited backup best practice: maintain 3 copies of the data (the original plus at least 2 backups), stored on 2 different media types (so a single media failure cannot destroy both copies), with 1 copy kept offsite (so a site-level disaster — fire, flood, theft, ransomware reaching the primary site — cannot destroy all copies). The modern extension is 3-2-1-1-0: adds 1 immutable or air-gapped copy (defense against ransomware that targets backups) and 0 errors verified (test restores confirm the backups are actually usable). Option B captures the rule correctly. Options A, C, D are made-up variants. The CISSP exam tests the 3-2-1 rule directly because it is a specific, well-known backup principle and because modern ransomware attacks have elevated backup protection to a top concern. Related concepts: backup immutability (AWS S3 Object Lock, Azure immutable blob, Google Cloud Storage retention policies), offsite vs off-network (both provide protection but against different threats), and the distinction between backup (for recovery from loss) and archive (for long-term retention).",
