    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Modern ransomware attacks specifically target backups as part of the attack: attackers gain access, locate backup systems, and either encrypt or delete backup data before triggering the ransomware payload — ensuring that victims cannot recover without paying. Traditional 3-2-1 (three copies, two media, one offsite) is necessary but not sufficient against this threat because network-accessible backups can be destroyed by the attacker with appropriate privileges. The modern extension 3-2-1-1-0 adds: 1 immutable or air-gapped copy that cannot be destroyed by an attacker with network access (AWS S3 Object Lock, Azure immutable blob storage with time locks, tape in a vault, or offline systems with write-once media); and 0 errors verified via regular test restores (because many organizations have backups that fail silently and are only discovered at the worst moment). Cloud replicated backups with verified integrity, explicit retention policies, and cryptographic signatures provide modern protection when configured correctly. Option B captures these improvements. Option A (more frequent) does not address the destruction risk. Option C (cloud only) removes physical diversity. Option D is the opposite of the correct direction. The CISSP exam tests backup modernization because ransomware has made it a current and critical topic.",
