    "explanation": "Patch decisions are risk decisions that must weigh vulnerability risk against operational impact. The mature approach: (1) assess vulnerability risk — is it actively exploited in the wild (check CISA KEV, threat intelligence feeds), is a public exploit available, is the system exposed to attackers who would use such exploits, what is the severity and impact if exploited; (2) assess operational impact of the outage — what business processes depend on this server during the affected window, what is the cost of the outage, can users be notified and work around it; (3) if vulnerability risk justifies the outage, proceed via emergency change management with scheduled downtime communication, rollback plan, and post-implementation verification; (4) if compensating controls can bridge to a planned maintenance window (WAF rule, network isolation, EDR blocking rule, increased monitoring), use them to avoid the business-hours outage and schedule the patch for the next window. Option B captures this risk-based approach. Option A (patch regardless) ignores business impact. Option C (ignore) is negligent. Option D (wait a year) is absurd. The CISSP exam tests patch management because it is a common operational decision that illustrates the balance between security and operations.",
