    "explanation": "External communication during an incident has outsized consequences: inaccurate statements become legal liability, inconsistent statements undermine trust, premature disclosures can harm the investigation, and uncoordinated communication creates regulatory exposure. The mature IR communication plan designates a single spokesperson — typically from communications or PR with support from legal and executive leadership — as the only person authorized to speak to external parties. Pre-drafted messaging reviewed by legal covers common scenarios (confirmed breach, suspected breach, contained, still investigating) and provides consistent, accurate language. The spokesperson is trained for high-pressure media and customer interactions and understands the legal constraints. Everyone else is instructed to redirect inquiries to the spokesperson — including security analysts, engineers, and managers who may have partial information but lack the authorization or training to speak publicly. Option B captures this. Option A (everyone with knowledge) produces chaos and legal exposure. Option C (first analyst) bypasses the chain. Option D (any manager) lacks the specialization and authorization. The CISSP exam tests IR communications because it is a specific, testable discipline and because real incidents frequently suffer from uncoordinated external communication.",
