    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Investigation readiness requires logs from the specific sources an investigation will need. For a cloud-hosted application, the critical sources are: (1) authentication logs from the identity provider — who logged in, when, from where, with what outcome, what MFA state; (2) cloud control plane logs (AWS CloudTrail, Azure Activity Log, GCP Audit Log) that record every API call to the cloud provider — essential for detecting configuration changes, unauthorized access, and attacker actions in the cloud environment; (3) network flow logs that record connections between hosts; (4) application access logs that record application-level requests and responses; (5) security tool logs from EDR, DLP, IDS/IPS that provide tool-specific detection context. Retention must cover typical dwell times — advanced persistent threats often have dwell times of 100-200 days, so 30-day retention means most investigations will run out of evidence. Option B captures the mature logging strategy. Option A (debug only) misses almost everything important. Option C (firewall only) is a narrow subset. Option D (cheap to store) optimizes cost at the expense of investigation capability. The CISSP exam tests logging strategy because it is specific to security operations and because 'collect everything' is an anti-pattern while 'collect too little' is the more common failure.",
