    "explanation": "DR plan degradation over time is a well-known failure mode. Plans that are not tested regularly diverge from operational reality because: (1) personnel turnover means the people who knew the plan are gone and new people do not; (2) system changes (new applications, retired applications, upgraded platforms, changed dependencies) mean the plan's steps no longer match the current environment; (3) network changes (new segments, changed routing, new security controls) break the failover procedures; (4) backup technology or vendor changes leave the plan referencing things that no longer exist; (5) the plan documents assumptions that are no longer true. A plan that has not been tested in 18 months is essentially untested — its correctness against current reality is unknown. Regular testing is the only way to keep the plan aligned: progressively from checklist review (paper verification) through tabletop (discussion) through walkthrough through simulation through parallel test (full execution in secondary while primary continues) through full interruption test (actual failover). Each level catches different kinds of drift. Option B captures the root cause. Option A (RTO unrealistic) blames the target; the correct framing is that the plan could not meet the target because it was not maintained. Options C and D do not match the scenario. The CISSP exam tests DR testing because it is a recurring real-world failure mode.",
