    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "Lateral movement — the attacker's progression from an initial compromised host to other internal systems — happens inside the network, not at the perimeter. Perimeter firewalls see the initial entry but do not see internal east-west traffic, which is where lateral movement lives. The most valuable sources of visibility are: (1) east-west network traffic visibility — internal network flow logs (NetFlow, IPFIX, VPC Flow Logs in cloud), service mesh telemetry (Istio, Linkerd) for microservices environments, micro-segmentation audit logs that show which workloads are communicating; (2) endpoint detection on both the source and destination of lateral movement — EDR agents see process spawns, credential use, and file system operations that indicate an attacker moving laterally; (3) authentication logs from the identity provider showing unusual access patterns across multiple systems by the same principal, which is a high-fidelity signal for credential compromise and lateral movement. Option B captures these sources. Option A (perimeter firewall) misses the entire east-west picture. Option C is the same error. Option D (SIEM alerts) is a downstream consumer of the underlying logs and is only as good as the log sources feeding it. The CISSP exam tests lateral movement detection because it is current (ransomware, APT) and because the correct answer specifically rejects the perimeter-centric framing.",
