    "explanation": "Law enforcement engagement during a security incident is a nuanced decision with real trade-offs. The right times to engage include: (1) when there is clear evidence of a crime, especially federal offenses under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act or similar statutes; (2) when legal counsel advises it based on the specific facts and jurisdiction; (3) when specific regulations require it (certain critical infrastructure sectors, NIS2 for EU essential services, SEC material-incident disclosure which may trigger related reporting); (4) when law enforcement coordination would benefit the investigation (they may have intelligence about the actor, they may be able to coordinate with foreign authorities if the attacker is international) or provide prosecutorial leverage (deterrence, recovery of assets, public-private cooperation). Engagement should be coordinated through legal counsel — not directly by technical staff — because legal counsel manages privilege, discovery implications, and coordinated communication. Trade-offs include potential loss of control over the investigation timeline (law enforcement may delay public disclosure to preserve their case), disclosure of sensitive internal information in affidavits, and the possibility that the case does not result in actionable prosecution. Option B captures this nuanced framing. Options A, C, D are oversimplified. The CISSP exam tests law enforcement engagement because it is a specific IR decision with real consequences.",
