    "explanation": "Direct-to-production patch deployment without testing is a leading cause of self-inflicted outages. Patches occasionally break things — compatibility issues with other software, changed APIs, performance regressions, dependency conflicts — and discovering these breakages in production affects every user immediately. The mature approach is a tested rollout: (1) test environment that mirrors production, so patches can be validated against production-like configuration before deployment; (2) automated regression testing where possible, including functional tests, performance benchmarks, and security smoke tests; (3) staged rollout: canary (one or a few instances, monitored closely), small percentage (5-10% of the fleet, monitored for outliers), broader deployment (25-50%), full deployment (100%) — with explicit pause criteria and rollback at each stage; (4) rollback procedures tested in advance so that a bad deployment can be reversed quickly; (5) post-deployment verification to confirm the patch is effective and no new issues have emerged. Option B captures this. Option A (stop patching) is negligent. Option C (annual) leaves known vulnerabilities unpatched for most of the year. Option D is worse. The CISSP exam tests patch management testing because it is specific and because the self-inflicted outage failure mode is common.",
