    "explanation": "DR program effectiveness cannot be proven without real disasters, which are rare by definition. The effective substitute is regular testing at progressively increasing levels of realism, with explicit measurement at each level. Tabletop exercises test whether the team can reason through a scenario and identify the right actions. Walkthroughs test whether the documented procedures are accurate. Simulations test whether partial execution of the plan works against real (if limited) conditions. Parallel tests execute recovery in a secondary environment while primary operations continue — a full operational test without risking the primary. Full interruption tests are the most realistic: they shut down primary to force actual failover, which is expensive and risky but provides the strongest evidence. At each level, measurement should include: were objectives met (RTO, RPO, functional completeness), were gaps identified (what needed to happen but could not), were remediations tracked to completion (gaps become improvement actions). Tracking improvement over time as gaps are closed and more ambitious exercises are run is the program's effectiveness story. Option B captures this. Option A (wait for real) sacrifices measurement. Option C (ask if they feel prepared) is subjective. Option D (page count) is frivolous. The CISSP exam tests DR measurement because it is a specific governance requirement and because regular testing is the only valid substitute for real disasters.",
