    "explanation": "Vendor incident response clauses are critical because the customer's incident response depends on vendor cooperation for any incident involving vendor-hosted data or systems. Without contractual obligations, vendors may be slow, defensive, or uncooperative — exactly when the customer needs speed and transparency. The key clauses: (1) specific breach notification SLA — typically 24 to 72 hours from the vendor's discovery of an incident affecting customer data, with specific escalation if uncertainty exists; (2) defined support obligations during the customer's incident response — providing logs, cooperating with forensic investigation, providing access to the vendor's environment if necessary, maintaining a point of contact; (3) forensic evidence preservation obligations — committing to preserve evidence for a specified period, not destroying logs or overwriting relevant data; (4) right-to-audit after an incident so the customer can verify the vendor's claims about scope and root cause; (5) clear liability and indemnification terms that specify financial responsibility. Option B captures these. Options A, C, D are frivolous. The CISSP exam tests vendor IR clauses because they are specific to vendor management and because many real-world incidents have suffered from inadequate vendor cooperation due to weak contracts. Related: the contracts should be exercised in tabletop exercises with the vendor to validate that the contractual obligations translate to operational readiness.",
