    "explanation": "Post-incident reviews are one of the most valuable opportunities for program improvement, but only if the review surfaces honest information about what happened. Blame-focused reviews drive silence: people avoid admitting mistakes, hide information, and deflect responsibility, which means the review captures surface symptoms rather than root causes. Blameless post-mortems — a practice popularized in SRE culture and increasingly adopted in security — focus on root cause analysis that treats individual mistakes as symptoms of systemic issues. The assumption is that people do their best given the tools, training, incentives, and context they have; when someone makes a mistake, the question is 'what about the system allowed or caused this mistake' rather than 'who is to blame'. The mature post-incident review: (1) gathers facts first, without judgment; (2) identifies root causes that could be addressed to prevent recurrence; (3) captures contributing factors that made the incident worse; (4) produces specific remediation actions with named owners and realistic deadlines; (5) tracks remediation to completion as a closed loop; (6) publishes a sanitized summary so the whole organization benefits from the learning. Option B captures this. Option A drives silence. Option C drives underreporting. Option D is beside the point. The CISSP exam tests post-incident reviews because they are central to program improvement and because the blameless principle is specific and well-defined.",
