    "explanation": "A SOC producing 5000 alerts with capacity for 100 has a signal-to-noise problem, not a capacity problem. Adding more analysts is an expensive non-fix because the root cause is detection rules that produce too many low-fidelity alerts. The correct remediation is tuning-first: (1) review detection rules to identify those producing high false-positive rates, and tune, suppress, or retire them — a rule that produces 500 alerts per day with 99% false positives should be questioned; (2) prioritize high-fidelity indicators that map to real attack patterns (EDR behavioral alerts, identity anomalies, specific MITRE ATT&CK techniques) over noisy patterns (generic port scans, common web attacks); (3) deploy SOAR to automate enrichment (add context to alerts) and initial triage (close obvious false positives automatically, escalate high-fidelity alerts to human attention); (4) implement alert grouping and suppression so that duplicate or related events are collapsed into a single case rather than generating individual alerts; (5) measure signal-to-noise ratio as a primary SOC KPI — the percentage of alerts that lead to real investigation — and track improvement over time. Option B captures this. Option A (more analysts) scales the problem. Options C and D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests this because alert fatigue is one of the most common SOC failure modes and the correct answer is detection engineering, not headcount.",
