    "explanation": "Customer-managed keys in the cloud provider's KMS provide real benefits over provider-managed keys: the customer controls key policy, rotation, and access. But the key material lives inside the cloud provider's infrastructure, which means: (1) the cloud provider has technical access to the keys at some level — their KMS implementation uses their infrastructure, their people operate it, and their incident response can touch it; (2) legal compulsion of the provider (subpoena, CLOUD Act order, foreign government request) could compel key use; (3) KMS compromise (insider access, KMS-specific vulnerability, supply-chain attack on the KMS implementation) would expose the keys. For backups that must survive these threats — particularly regulated industries concerned with government access or ransomware attacks on the cloud account itself — client-side encryption with keys held outside the cloud provider's environment provides stronger guarantees. The provider sees only ciphertext and cannot produce plaintext even under legal compulsion or insider abuse. This pattern is sometimes called 'Hold Your Own Key' (HYOK) and is appropriate when the threat model includes the cloud provider as a potential adversary. Option B captures the specific concern. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests this because the trust boundary of cloud encryption is a specific and current topic with real consequences.",
