    "explanation": "Cloud-native monitoring requires visibility at multiple layers because threats manifest at different layers and because cloud environments produce telemetry at layers that traditional monitoring missed. The comprehensive strategy: (1) cloud control plane — API calls, resource changes, IAM events; an attacker who compromises cloud credentials manipulates the control plane and these logs catch them; (2) network — VPC flow logs show connections between workloads, DNS queries show name resolution (and potential exfiltration), egress shows outbound traffic; (3) application — authentication and authorization events, error rates, business events that map to user intent; (4) workload — container events, process behavior, syscall monitoring if enabled; attackers who land on a workload manipulate processes and files; (5) identity — IdP logs, MFA events, anomalous access patterns; many attacks target identity; (6) data — access to sensitive datasets, query patterns, exfiltration indicators. Integration into unified detection and correlation means that a single investigation can pivot across all layers to understand the full scope of an event. Option B captures the layered approach. Option A (only application) misses the cloud control plane, network, and identity layers. Options C and D are narrow subsets. The CISSP exam tests cloud monitoring because cloud has specific telemetry that traditional programs miss.",
