    "explanation": "Incident-specific playbooks are a mature IR practice because different incident types have different characteristics, stakeholders, and response patterns. A single generic playbook cannot capture the specific details each incident type requires. The correct approach develops playbooks for the incident types the organization is most likely to face: (1) ransomware — the dominant threat; includes containment, eradication, recovery from backups, negotiation decisions, and regulatory notification; (2) BEC (Business Email Compromise) and phishing — includes email forensics, financial recovery (urgent — wire transfer reversal has short windows), fraud department engagement, and communication to affected parties; (3) credential compromise — includes credential rotation, session revocation, account monitoring, and propagation analysis; (4) data exfiltration — includes scope assessment, evidence preservation, notification analysis, and affected party communication; (5) insider threat — includes HR coordination, legal engagement, evidence preservation in employment-legal terms; (6) DDoS — includes upstream coordination, scrubbing services, customer communication; (7) cloud compromise — includes cloud-specific IR actions (key rotation, IAM changes, resource tagging for investigation); (8) supply chain — includes third-party coordination and scope determination. Each playbook should be rehearsed in tabletop exercises. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests playbook development because it is specific to IR maturity.",
