    "explanation": "Publishing incident response information externally involves the same transparency-vs-operational-security trade-off as other security disclosures (Domain 6). Publishing a full IR plan exposes information that aids attackers: specific tools used, detection rules, containment thresholds, escalation patterns, and operational playbook contents that let attackers design around them. Publishing nothing sacrifices the trust-building benefit and the accountability to customers and regulators. The mature approach publishes a high-level summary: (1) principles — the organization's approach to IR, commitment to transparency with customers, and commitment to timely notification; (2) team structure — the existence of an IR team (or reference to an MSSP) without naming individuals or specific tools; (3) commitment to timely notification — specific SLAs for customer notification, regulatory notification where applicable, and approximate timelines; (4) frameworks followed — NIST SP 800-61, ISO 27035, industry-specific standards; (5) customer support commitments during an incident — how customers can reach the organization, what information they will receive, what their obligations are. Detailed operational information (specific tools, playbook content, detection thresholds, escalation procedures) remains internal. Option B captures this balance. Options A (full), C (nothing), D (decoy) are wrong. The CISSP exam tests this because transparency is a real business pressure and the mature answer is specific.",
