    "explanation": "The build-vs-buy SIEM decision is a legitimate strategic question with trade-offs on both sides. Building with open-source components (Elasticsearch/Logstash/Kibana, Wazuh, OpenSearch, Grafana Loki, Prometheus, and similar) offers: no license fees, full customization, ownership of the data and processing pipeline, flexibility to integrate with any source. But building has real costs: significant engineering effort to build detection content (rules, correlation logic, dashboards), ongoing maintenance to keep content current with new threats and tool changes, infrastructure scaling as log volume grows, and operational expertise to run production-grade infrastructure. Many organizations under-estimate the total cost and discover that 'free' software has significant hidden costs. Commercial SIEMs (Splunk, Microsoft Sentinel, IBM QRadar, Sumo Logic, Elastic Cloud, Google Chronicle) offer: faster time-to-value with pre-built content, vendor-maintained detection updates, professional support, scalability without operational burden, and integration ecosystems. But they have higher direct costs, less customization, and can create lock-in. The decision depends on organization scale (very large organizations may justify building), engineering capacity (do you have the team to build and maintain), and differentiation requirements (is your use case unusual enough to need custom tooling). Many organizations land on hybrid models: commercial SIEM as the core with custom content and integrations. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are oversimplified.",
