    "explanation": "Vendor reliance has significant and specific effects on incident response that many organizations underestimate. The key affected areas: (1) access — during an incident, the organization may need access to vendor-hosted systems, logs, configurations, and staff. Without pre-negotiated agreements, access requests may take days or weeks, during which evidence degrades and the incident worsens. (2) Logs — vendor-held logs are often required for full investigation scope, and vendor willingness and ability to share them quickly varies. (3) Containment actions — isolation, credential rotation, and other containment may require vendor cooperation, and vendor response time adds latency to the organization's response. (4) Contracts — must specify IR support obligations, breach notification SLAs (from vendor to customer), evidence preservation obligations, and right-to-audit. Without these, the organization has no contractual lever during an incident. (5) Tabletop exercises — should include vendor scenarios where the vendor is involved, contacted, and coordinated with, so that the process is exercised before a real incident. (6) Accountability — the organization retains regulatory and customer accountability regardless of whether execution happens internally or at a vendor. A vendor failure does not excuse the organization from its obligations. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests vendor IR because third-party incidents are common and well-documented.",
