    "explanation": "Customer communication during active incidents is one of the hardest aspects of incident response because the organization has strong pressures in both directions — legal and strategic pressures to say less, customer and reputation pressures to say more. The mature approach avoids both failure modes: (1) timely acknowledgment that something is happening, so customers know the organization is aware and responding; silence longer than the incident duration damages trust catastrophically; (2) specify what is known and what is not — separate verified facts from unverified reports, separate impact assessments from speculation, separate current state from projected outcomes; (3) commit to regular updates on a defined cadence (hourly, every four hours, daily depending on severity) so customers know when to expect new information; (4) single point of contact for customer inquiries — a customer support channel, a status page, a dedicated email address — so that the organization has consistent messaging; (5) update the communication as facts develop, correcting earlier information when new facts emerge; (6) legal and PR review of customer communication before publication, to ensure consistency and accuracy. Option B captures this balanced approach. Options A and C are opposite failure modes. Option D is too absolute — some information is genuinely not appropriate to share in real time. The CISSP exam tests incident communication because it is a specific, testable discipline and because real incidents are frequently damaged by poor communication choices.",
