    "explanation": "Acquisitions inherit both assets and risks. Before integration, the parent company should conduct a thorough security assessment of the acquired environment: (1) asset inventory — what systems exist, where, who owns them; acquisitions frequently have shadow IT and undocumented systems; (2) identity data — who has access to what, including orphaned accounts from the acquired company's own lifecycle gaps; (3) known vulnerabilities and unpatched systems — inherited technical debt; (4) incident history — has the acquired company had security incidents, and are any still active or recent (the Marriott/Starwood 2018 pattern); (5) third-party dependencies — what vendors and sub-processors the acquired company uses, and whether they are acceptable under the parent's standards; (6) compliance obligations — what regulations apply and whether the acquired company is compliant; (7) any active or recent incidents that the parent company would be inheriting. The assessment results feed integration planning: which systems to migrate first, which to decommission, which to leave in place temporarily, and what remediation priorities to schedule. Immediate application of parent policies is inappropriate because it may break business functions the parent does not yet understand, and because the parent's policies may not fit the acquired company's operational reality. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests M&A security because it is a common real-world scenario with real consequences.",
