    "correct_index": 1,
    "explanation": "DR site geographic separation is a core consideration because the purpose of the DR site is to survive scenarios that destroy or impair the primary. If both sites are in the same metropolitan area, they share the same regional hazards: (1) earthquakes — the same fault line affects both; (2) hurricanes — the same storm path affects both; (3) flooding — the same watershed or coastal surge affects both; (4) large-scale power outages — the same grid supplies both; (5) regional network failures — the same backbone failures affect both; (6) regional terrorism or civil unrest — the same events affect both. Hurricane Katrina in 2005 taught this lesson painfully: organizations with DR sites in the same coastal region lost both primary and secondary simultaneously. The correct separation depends on the hazards the organization plans for: for significant hazards (hurricanes, earthquakes), separation of hundreds of miles is typical; for more localized events (building fires, localized utility failures), less separation may be acceptable. Many organizations use a two-tier approach: a nearby site for operational recovery from localized events, and a distant site for regional disasters. Option B captures this. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests DR site selection because it is specific, well-defined, and frequently gets wrong in real-world programs that prioritize operational convenience over disaster planning.",
