    "explanation": "Phishing response is a high-volume activity that benefits from automation, but not all steps are appropriate to fully automate. The value pattern: (1) acknowledge the report — automatable, high value because it confirms to users that their reports are received and encourages more reporting (the leading indicator of phishing program health); (2) analyze the message for known IOCs — automatable, fast and accurate; (3) check whether other users received the same message — automatable, scalable; catches broad campaigns quickly; (4) add IOCs to block lists — automatable for well-established indicators, with human review for novel indicators to avoid false positives; (5) scan affected mailboxes — automatable; (6) reserve human review for ambiguous cases (what does this message mean, is it a legitimate vendor email or a BEC attempt), high-impact cases (targeting executives or finance staff with specific knowledge of ongoing transactions), and cases where remediation requires judgment about user communication (the communication affects employees and must not be heavy-handed). The right balance automates scale work and reserves human attention for judgment work. Option B captures this. Option A (automate everything) may create false positives and user communication problems. Option C (nothing) cannot scale. Option D (only reporting) misses most of the value. The CISSP exam tests automation choices because they are specific and because the mature answer is selective.",
