    "explanation": "The OWASP Top 10 2021 edition ranked Broken Access Control as A01, the most common web application security risk, moving it up from A05 in the 2017 edition. Broken Access Control covers failures in enforcing authorization — users accessing resources or performing actions they should not be permitted to. Examples include IDOR (Insecure Direct Object References), privilege escalation, accessing admin panels without authorization, bypassing access control checks through URL manipulation, and API endpoints missing authorization enforcement. Option A (Injection) was A01 in 2017 but was moved to A03 in 2021 as frameworks have improved default protection. Option C (SSRF) was new in 2021 at A10. Option D (Security Misconfiguration) moved from A06 to A05. The CISSP exam tests the OWASP Top 10 ranking because it reflects the current threat landscape and because candidates should know the relative prevalence of web application risk categories. Memorize at least the top five: A01 Broken Access Control, A02 Cryptographic Failures, A03 Injection, A04 Insecure Design, A05 Security Misconfiguration.",
