    "explanation": "Test environments that share data with production create multiple security and privacy risks: (1) DAST tools that send test payloads (injection strings, fuzzing, enumeration) may interact with production data via the shared database, potentially corrupting or disclosing it; (2) test user accounts may access real customer data, violating privacy obligations under GDPR, HIPAA, and similar regulations; (3) test environment security controls are typically weaker than production (wider access, less monitoring, more permissive configurations), exposing production data to a weaker control environment; (4) test results may contain production data fragments that are then shared with developers, testers, or third parties. The correct approach: (1) test environments use synthetic or anonymized data that preserves data distributions for realistic testing without exposing real customer information; (2) the network boundary between test and production prevents any data flow from production to test except through a controlled, privacy-preserving pipeline; (3) access controls on test environments are appropriate for the data they contain, not relaxed because 'it is just test'. Option B captures the concern. Options A, C, D are wrong. The CISSP exam tests environment isolation because it is a specific, well-defined development security practice.",
